Gandalf61 ( talk ) Etymology  1.
On introducing Shakespeare's, Macbeth, Macbeth rode out upon the "heath" (a plane), "line" against line (a line of Kerns, a military line of men) , "point against point" (a point is a spear or javelin) , "lapp'd  in proof ".
An emeritus Shakespeare scholar at UCLA claimed Shakespeare was talking about geometry, and the metaphor was armor against the false, developed further in the story.
Does anyone have anything to contribute as a section of this article regarding the etymology or early history of "proof", armour against false propositions, other than use in law?
2.
Hacking discusses "probity" in relation to "probability", with ironic etymology.
But more interesting is that "probity" comes from God without empirical test, like proofs were once thought to.
Does anyone know more about this relationship?
The parallel would agrue against coincidence.
I included this fact in the article without stating the inference from the fact.
Tautologist ( talk ) 19:48, 3 October 2008 (UTC)  I am suspicious of the etymology in the article.
Hacking does not seem to derive the word from probare , although he does refer to the meaning of test .
We need a lexicographical citation.
I don't find it in the OED or Chambers for Mathematical proof.
Myrvin ( talk ) 10:52, 12 July 2009 (UTC)   Websters 1913 edition has same etymology.
as does the The Century Dictionary, 1911.
 and wikitionary wikt:proof .-- Salix ( talk ): 17:58, 12 July 2009 (UTC)   Yes I also found it in the New Shorter OED.
